<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">03 — Technology</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">What Makes La Cornue Different to Service</h2>
    <p class="section-lead">La Cornue's Parisian handcraft tradition, vaulted oven design, and serial-specific engineering create service requirements unique in the residential appliance world.</p>

    <div class="features-2col">
      <ul class="features-list">
        <li><strong>Vaulted (Arched) Oven Ceiling</strong> — La Cornue's defining innovation from 1908: the arched oven cavity creates natural convection circulation without a fan. Heat rises, follows the arch, and flows down the sides — enveloping food from all angles. The dome geometry also means heat stratification behaves differently than in a rectangular oven. A standard oven temperature test at one height gives a misleading reading; we use multi-point measurement across the dome to accurately characterize La Cornue oven performance.</li>
        <li><strong>Serial-Specific Parts Architecture</strong> — La Cornue updates component specifications at specific serial number milestones — not just major model revisions. Gaskets, safety valves, and control components can differ between units produced six months apart. This is more granular than most brands' part revision history. We identify the serial number plate (inside the left storage drawer) before ordering any La Cornue part — especially gaskets and thermocouples.</li>
        <li><strong>French Top as Independent System</strong> — The French Top plate is fed by a dedicated burner with its own thermocouple and gas circuit — independent from the main range burner control. When the French top loses temperature, the diagnosis is in the dedicated circuit, not the main range system. The graduated heat zones (hot center to warm edge) depend on both correct burner output and proper plate seasoning. Both are service considerations specific to the French top.</li>
        <li><strong>Château Custom Build Documentation</strong> — Every Château is built to a specific customer order — which means service sometimes requires understanding what La Cornue's Saint-Ouen workshop built for that particular range. For Château configurations with uncommon burner arrangements, custom dimensions, or bespoke accessories, the original build specification is the reference document. We work with La Cornue USA's service support to identify correct parts for unusual Château configurations.</li>
        <li><strong>Enamel from Saint-Ouen</strong> — La Cornue's enamel is produced and applied in the Saint-Ouen workshop — not a third-party coating. Custom Château colors are color-matched and mixed for each order. When a Château enamel panel needs replacement, the Saint-Ouen workshop produces a new panel to the original color specification. Lead times reflect this production process: typically several months for custom Château color panels.</li>
        <li><strong>Thermocouple System</strong> — Like ILVE and Lacanche, La Cornue uses Italian and French-spec thermocouples with specific millivolt output requirements. We test thermocouple output before replacing — confirming degradation rather than replacing based on symptoms alone. La Cornue thermocouple replacement requires awareness of the gas circuit architecture specific to each series.</li>
      </ul>
      <div>
        <div class="tip-block" style="background:#0a0a1a; border-color:#2a5ea5; margin-top:0">
          <div class="tip-label" style="color:#6aabff">🏛️ La Cornue vs Lacanche in LA</div>
          <div class="tip-text" style="color:#bbb">Both are French luxury ranges handcrafted in France — Lacanche in Burgundy, La Cornue near Paris. The practical distinctions for LA owners and service: La Cornue is positioned higher — the Château especially is among the most expensive residential ranges in the world. La Cornue's vaulted oven is unique to the brand; Lacanche uses a conventional oven cavity. Lacanche's brass jets require more frequent LA maintenance than La Cornue's sealed burner system. Both require serial-specific parts knowledge. Both deserve technicians who know the specific product — not just "French range service" generally. We service both.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tip-block" style="background:#1a0a0a; border-color:#c8820a; margin-top:16px">
          <div class="tip-label" style="color:#e8a030">🏡 La Cornue in LA — Where These Ranges Live</div>
          <div class="tip-text" style="color:#bbb">La Cornue's LA presence is concentrated in the homes of people for whom the kitchen is genuinely important — serious cooks in Bel Air and Beverly Hills who commissioned a custom Château as the centerpiece of a kitchen renovation, Malibu estate kitchens designed around entertainment, and Brentwood and Pacific Palisades homes where a CornuFé coordinates with a broader French design direction. La Cornue owners know exactly what they have. They chose it for specific reasons. When it needs service, they want a technician who matches their investment with equivalent knowledge.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

