    <h2 class="section-title">La Cornue Repair FAQ</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between Château and CornuFé?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Château is La Cornue's fully bespoke line — each range is built to order in Saint-Ouen with virtually unlimited customization. CornuFé is the semi-standard line in 90cm and 110cm with curated options. Both use the vaulted oven and are handcrafted in France. Service differs: Château serial numbers are critical for all parts ordering; CornuFé has standardized parts with specific serial-number thresholds for gaskets and safety components.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why does La Cornue use serial-specific parts?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">La Cornue updated component specifications at production milestones — not only at model revisions. CornuFé 90 and 110 gaskets have different part numbers before and after specific serial numbers (185000 and 196000 respectively). Château gaskets changed specification in July 2021. Using the wrong serial-era gasket creates a door that appears closed but doesn't seal correctly, causing temperature drift. We verify serial numbers before ordering any La Cornue gasket or safety valve.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">My La Cornue oven is baking unevenly — top too hot, bottom too cool. What's wrong?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The thermostat probe may have shifted in the dome, or the door gasket is failing (allowing air infiltration that affects dome heat circulation). We do a multi-point temperature test at seven positions across the dome before any diagnosis — standard single-point testing doesn't accurately characterize La Cornue's vaulted cavity. Probe repositioning resolves many La Cornue baking inconsistency calls without parts.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is La Cornue's French Top?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The French Top (Piano Top) is a solid cast iron cooking plate heated from below by a dedicated burner — creating graduated heat zones from searing-hot center to gentle-warm edge. It's fed by its own burner, thermocouple, and gas circuit. French top failures are specific to the dedicated system: jet blockage, thermocouple degradation, or surface seasoning unevenness. We diagnose the French top independently from the main burner system.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Where is La Cornue made?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Saint-Ouen, in the northern suburbs of Paris, France. Albert Dupuy founded La Cornue there in 1908, inventing the first convection oven with a vaulted ceiling. Every La Cornue range — Château and CornuFé — is handcrafted at the Saint-Ouen workshop.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How long does it take to get La Cornue parts?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Standard parts (thermocouples, standard gaskets, igniters) through La Cornue USA: typically 1–3 weeks. Serial-specific components: 2–4 weeks. Custom Château enamel panels and bespoke configuration components: production lead time from Saint-Ouen, typically 2–4 months. We verify availability before quoting timelines and disclose honestly before any parts are ordered.</div>
